Exceptions
----------

   The following example defines a predicate in C that converts a
list of codes into a number using `strtol()'. If this conversion
fails, then a exception is raised.

   *File* _exceptions_example.pl_:

   :- module(exceptions_example,         [codes_to_number_c/2,
 safe_codes_to_number/2         ],         [foreign_interface]).

   :- use_module(library(format)).

   % If the string is not a number raises an exception.  :- true pred
codes_to_number_c(in(X), go(Y)) :: string * int + (foreign,
returns(Y)).

   safe_codes_to_number(X, Y) :-         catch(codes_to_number_c(X,
Y), Error, handle_exception(Error)).

   handle_exception(Error) :- format("Exception caught ~w~n",
[Error]).

   :- use_foreign_source(exceptions_c).  :-
extra_compiler_opts('-O2').

   *File* _exceptions_c.c_:

   #include <string.h> #include "ciao_prolog.h"

   int codes_to_number_c(char *s) {   char *endptr;   int n;   n =
strtol(s,  10);   if (endptr == NULL || *endptr != '\0') {
ciao_raise_exception(ciao_structure("codes_to_number_exception",
                                  1,
       ciao_atom(s)));   }   return n; }


